They wish to calm investors before the beginning of trade in Asian financial markets, which are located in the first time zone, where Congress' decision could affect Monday's trade.
For the moment, however, it is impossible to clarify with certainty when the two Chambers of the United States Congress will vote, or if the negotiations are not likely to remain blocked at the last moment by a particular problem.
The legislators hope that it will be adopted in the coming days.
However, the law will still have many amendments.
The total amount intended for use by the system shall be divided into two parts.
The first $350 billion, as President George Bush wanted, must be made available as soon as possible.
But if Congress feels that the program does not perform its function, it has the opportunity to block the remaining amount by two steps: first an additional $100 billion, then, finally, $350 billion.
Mr. Bush welcomed progress in the negotiations
