The House of Representatives should be able to vote on Sunday, and the Senate on Monday," said Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
American President George Bush himself is pleased with the progress in the negotiations.
His spokesman Tony Fratto said that Mr. Bush was pleased with the progress made on Saturday and appreciated "the bipartite effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy".
Limitation of golden parachutes
Senate Banking Committee Chair Christopher Dodd, Chief Negotiator, said that legislators agreed on the responsibility of the financial program, the protection of contributors against losses, the settlement agreement, the progress of the plan on the axis of time.
The new law also provides for the limitation of such golden parachutes for directors of the companies participating in the program and establishes a committee to monitor the fund.
The latter should be managed by the Ministry of Finance.
"We have worked very hard on this issue and made significant progress towards an agreement that will work and be effective for the market and for all Americans," said Paulson.
The plan also provides assistance for real estate owners, who have problems to pay for.
The government should negotiate new advances in the case of mortgages it will buy back, while reducing the monthly payments of the debtors and allowing them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological assistance
According to Patria Finance Chief Economist David Marek, the proposed plan is a good idea, but its realization will be very difficult.
"And this is due to the fact that it is not known what the mechanism and price of buy-back of problem assets will be.
This point will be decisive in deciding on the sharing of losses between the financial sector and the government," says Marek, this week, at the iHNed.cz server.
If the plan is adopted now, or at the beginning of next week, it is, according to Marek, not as important as that.
"It is much more important that congressmen agree this week that they support this plan and that we will devote it as soon as possible.
This psychological significance of the agreement, providing for the adoption of the plan, matters most at the moment," Marek stressed.
A fight pushed to the extreme: MP3 players against mobiles.
We'll advise you, how to choose
While virtually all mobiles can read MP3 files, no MP3 player can call.
It seems clear from this that it is better to buy only one phone.
However, there are sufficient reasons to obtain an independent reader.
The choice depends entirely on the mode of use and the requirements of the future owner.
It would be absurd to buy for the house a high-end expensive gramophone to put the new album of Maxim Turbulenc.
On the one hand, such musical products do not come out on vinyl disc, and, from the point of view of quality, there is no objective reason for this to happen.
Now, if there's vinyl discs stuck in your shelves, with rock art, jazz or blues, you're probably dreaming of such a gramophone.
The same is true of music during movements, i.e. compressed music, to say it in a simplified way - music in MP3.
There are also categories according to price and quality.
For one, it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand kroner for a reader, just as a Pink Floyd fan would have difficulty supporting earphones purchased for twenty kroner at the market.
These are two extremes, among which there is enough room for everyone.
The choice is wide.
Battery life is also decisive
Some top-of-the-range music players are capable of much more than just playing music, but these are unknown functions, of course, of most mobiles.
No current device is as universal as the phone.
Alongside the first functions, phone calls and SMS, it is able to read music and movies, record them, it has a camera of variable quality and can, for example, be used for navigation.
And if you consider Smartphones and communicators, you will have a small computer in your pocket.
Since no frigidaire can grill meat and no television will take photographs, we are witnessing a miracle.
However, the universal character of mobile is not without disadvantages.
The larger the number of functions you use, the smaller the interval between two recharges.
And the reading of music is one of the most important energy guilds.
There are few mobiles who are able to read music for ten to twelve hours, in most cases this figure is significantly lower.
In this regard, music players (especially the rudimentary ones) are significantly more effective.
In the case of cheap mobiles, count that they will only play music for a few hours.
If, in addition, you sometimes call from time to time, get, to be sure, a second recharge for work - this being valid even for the most expensive devices.
The problem will not arise for MP3 players, who are capable, following a recharge, of a continuous operation of at least 9 hours, including the least performing.
Another problem occurs when recording music in the mobile.
Unfortunately, a limited part of the devices has a universal USB connector, especially since not all can be directly connected to the computer, without special software.
Of course, music can be recorded directly on the memory card, but few card readers know how to do it without reduction, given the tiny dimensions of memory cards used in mobiles.
As far as readers are concerned, you do not need, except for (iPod), any software.
Simply fill, through the USB connector, the music device from the computer.
Most mobiles and readers will themselves create a media library classified according to the name of the performer, the title of the album, the style, or then the user's judgment.
Some devices only display an index with a tree structure, like Windows Explorer, others are capable of both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with operating system).
Readers are easier to handle, mobiles have more know-how
In choosing a specific device, you are particularly interested in the lifespan of the accumulator, the capacity of memory, the quality and type of sound output and, of course, the ease of ordering.
If the music is for you, essentially, a background noise and if in the day you will listen to it that for a limited time, for example by taking the tram, you just need any mobile reading the MP3s.
Virtually all mobiles are capable of doing so today.
You don't even have to pay too much attention to the music formats that the mobile or reader is able to read.
Everyone gets to read the MP3 and the vast majority of the music that will reach you will have exactly this format.
It is one of the most common formats, and apart from it, the vast majority of devices can also read WMA format music.
The AAFC (format used by Apple and its iPods) is less common.
High-end mobiles also allow, for example, the purchase of online music.
Simply visit, from the mobile phone, the corresponding web pages of the operator (or those of another provider) and buy the song or album in question.
This service alone should be a compelling reason to get a musical mobile.
The offer of operators is unfortunately miserable and is, in most cases, limited to radio tubes quickly made.
Prices are not the lowest either.
However, it is generally considered that this way of buying music (whether by GSM, Internet or even wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always wear their furniture on themselves.
Every time you want to listen to something, you just need to get the mobile out of your pocket, while you forgot your MP3 drive at home.
However, it is also important if you always have headphones or handsfree with connection.
If this is not the case, you can use built-in speakers, which have almost all mobile phones, but a minimum of MP3 players.
For many, the main advantage of musical mobiles is their price.
Less expensive people normally cost less than three thousand.
For a price of three four thousand crowns, you can have a walkman already very suitable.
In most cases, however, you will be limited by the absence of an output for ordinary headphones.
The price of the best phones and the best equipped, also equipped with an entrance for ordinary headphones, does not exceed fifteen thousand.
Readers, on the other hand, have the advantage of having an easy command.
Really anyone can secure the command of the most rudimentary readers - who do not necessarily correspond to the least expensive (cf. our choice).
A minimum of functions; and the resemblance of the command to that of a cassette station, commonly used in the past, or of a gramophone, is obvious.
There is no risk of collision in the form of a mobile Internet that is randomly connected, followed by an immense data transmission invoice.
Which device to choose
Even the cheapest mobiles (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for interchangeable memory cards (type M2, microSD, and so on).
Even taking into account the additional purchase of such a card, you will not exceed two thousand crowns.
But be careful.
In principle, the basic models only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB.
Only the most expensive ones get out even with 8 GB memory cards.
If you already own a mobile phone and still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, take a Cowon, a Creative, a Sony, a Samsung, an Emgeton, or a iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you should not spend more than 1,100 crowns.
If you are one of the most demanding listeners, choose more specialized mobile-walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices are equipped with independent control keys for MP3, and thus the ease of the control is closer to that of an independent MP3 drive.
Sony Ericsson, whose walkman series mobiles have the same user menu as MP3 players sold separately, is the one that went the furthest in this field.
The same service, in the same price category, but with a memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and a lifetime of the accumulator (normally 15 hours, up to 35 hours) above, is provided by an MP3 player produced by one of the above mentioned brands.
A first virtual operator will win the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in Chechnya is relatively advanced, with our operators offering almost the same services as their partners in Western Europe.
Despite this, we still lack something - a virtual operator, which would force conventional operators to lower prices.
Maybe he won't be missing for a long time.
We have already mentioned on many occasions on Mobil.cz that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
The ČTÚ (Czech Telecommunications Office), which reported that the price of a SMS was higher in our country than in the rest of the Union, confirmed it.
Thus, following the last steps of the European Commission in the field of roaming charges regulation, a paradoxical situation may occur - SMS sent from abroad will be for some customers of cheaper mobile operators than in the country.
How is it possible that prices in Chechnya remain so high, compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that would really want to enter the fight.
This may seem paradoxical, given that we still have three mobile networks and a penetration that far exceeds 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this, Pavel Dvořák, the President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ), who repeatedly stated that in Chechnya there was no place for another operator, cried with the operators.
It is probably true that a classical operator with his own network is apparently no longer very lucky (by the way, now he would find only frequencies difficult).
However, there is still a possibility - a virtual operator.
It was precisely the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that led to a considerable fall in prices, to which the traditional operators were then also to react.
However, even before the entrance of the riots such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile to the market, voices similar to those heard today at home were heard in Britain.
However, it appeared that there was still room for such operators and that they could have a real success.
We do not have to go too far to find examples.
In February we informed you of the launch in Poland of the virtual operator Mobilking.
In only six months, this operator managed to win over 100 thousand customers and become the fifth operator in the country.
Let's add that behind the Mobilking, there is the Penta financial group, which has among other things the U:fon in Chechnya.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility of focusing on a much more concrete target group.
For their operation to be effective, they need much less customers than a classic operator.
They are, in fact, exempt from the relatively high costs of construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
In this way, in the world, virtual operators profile themselves as low-cost operators - they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often counterbalanced by a limited service offer.
For example, Tesco Mobile offers SMS in Britain at least twice as expensive as its competitors.
But, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, betting on an unusual target group can also be a good publicity shot.
Indeed, this operator specifically targets men.
"The real men choose Mobilking - an operator they like and can trust," says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, operating this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say, if such a concept would be likely to work at home as well.
Miroslav Čepický, the spokesman for Vodafone, doubts: "The Czech market is relatively small for a segmental approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
Especially since it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the provision of services."
In Chechnya, no chance, mobile operators say
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual operator in Chechnya, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are discussing the expansion of this successful project, but in Chechnya the negotiations are not very encouraging.
Mobilking's launch will take place in other countries in our area," said in a telephone interview for Mobil.cz Jana Studničková, spokesperson for the Penta financial group.
It has thus indirectly confirmed that the operators in Chechnya were, in any case, not in favour of this idea.
On the contrary, they are trying to do everything possible to ensure that a potential competitor cannot appear.
The GTS Novera group, which would like to take a new step in order to become a real competitor of Telefonika in the field of customers, has not for a long time hidden its intention to launch a virtual mobile operator.
"We very much want to be able to offer our customers not only fixed but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner the better.
We have already conducted negotiations on this possibility on several occasions with all the Czech mobile operators.
With some, we have made progress in the negotiations," said the spokesman for the Pavel Kaidl Group.
So the future may be promising.
According to unofficial information, it seems that perhaps we could host the first virtual operator by the end of the year.
But for the moment, its creation is accompanied by a total silence.
"At the moment, we do not consider that there is room on the Czech market for a virtual operator as such.
The Czech market is in comparison with other very specific ones.
At the moment, no subject with a complex and serious project in this field has contacted us," said Vlastimil Sršeň of the press department of Telefonika O2, in his statement for Mobil.cz.
Other operators also relate to the specific nature of the Czech market.
T-Mobile's spokesman Martina Kemrová stated in a rare agreement with O2's statement: "We have not registered a viable and bilaterally advantageous project at the moment, which could serve as a basis."
She adds: "It is practically excluded that a virtual operator appears in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
In order to operate in such a limited period of time, we should now have a concrete agreement."
Vodafone instead directs his attention to the completion of the requests to obtain his own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický said: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, especially in the area of shared costs and infrastructure.
This, in our view, means the most input from the clients' point of view.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is the discovery of a partner to establish a common network for a fast mobile internet."
Responsible authorities: in phase with operators
The approach of mobile operators is easily understandable, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would have led to a decrease in prices and thus to a decrease in their profit.
So what good is it to facilitate the advent of such a competitor?
When it comes to their interests, operators know how to agree to themselves as fair thieves. The chicane accompanying the creation of the U:fon also bears witness to this.
The greatest apparent pressure on the ČTU, when the U:fon was created, was that exerted by T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by information available to the public from the ČTÚ web pages.
Today, however, the U:fon is ready to use as an argument not to accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová noted: "Competition on the mobile market has, moreover, recently been amplified by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile operator.
Given the character of the mobile market in RT, it is obvious that the entry of an additional player would subject it, and above all its services, to high requirements."
But given the attitude of the mobile operators here, the indifference of the Czech regulatory bodies seems disconcerting.
However, this is not just the attitude of the ČTÚ, which, unlike Britain and other developed countries, unfortunately does not have the power to intervene in economic competition in Chechnya.
It belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (UOHS).
However, the latter takes its typical position in the face of this problem.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible following the conclusion of an agreement between a mobile operator and the relevant virtual operator regarding the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such agreement has been reached at this time, as the offer of potential stakeholders has a priori not shown sufficient interest for conventional operators," said Kristián Chalupa of the UOHS Department of External Relations in response to our question.
A statement thus formulated would not surprise the representatives of the operators.
But on the part of an Office, which must represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, take care that no one takes advantage of its position on the market, such a declaration is more than confusing.
Especially since Kristián Chalupa adds: "At home, where virtual operators are normally present, it can be seen that their entry into the market has contributed to a decrease in the prices of mobile telephone services."
However, putting pressure on the honest functioning of the market and a fall in prices is apparently not one of the interests of UOHS.
What is actually shocking is the almost touching agreement of the three mobile operators, which stems from their reactions.
The question, if it really is a coincidence, arises naturally.
In the same way, a price of gasoline strictly identical to all service stations is probably due to chance and the hard fight of competition.
"The Office has not identified any signs of anticompetitive behaviour in this regard, so there is no reason to intervene in one way or another.
None of the operators has a dominant position, and therefore none has a corresponding increased responsibility for their behaviour on the market.
The tools needed to open the mobile market to virtual operators are probably not even missing from the telecommunications regulator," said Chalupa in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of the many points of disagreement.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by the ČTÚ that telecommunications is, from the point of view of economic competition, a single market.
None of the Czech operators has a dominant position on such a market.
However, some law experts suggest another vision of things: for the creation of a virtual operator to be possible, the consent of the network operator must be obtained at each time.
And the mobile operator has logically enough monopoly on his network.
Thus he necessarily plays a dominant role in a certain segment of his activity.
However, even without admitting this argument, it should be at least worrying for UOHS that three mobile operators are visibly proceeding in a similar way.
However, the complaints of many stakeholders (including GTS Novera, already mentioned) show that they face similar constraints in negotiations with all operators.
Resuming responsibility on the ČTÚ is a fairly common turn in communications, through which the UOHS washes its hands.
We have already encountered this type of attitude in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, it has not been possible to introduce a new telecommunications law, recently adopted, to extend the powers of the ČTÚ in the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although many specialists promised to improve the situation.
UOHS representatives must know that, but their interests seem to be elsewhere.
When no one looks, it can work.
However, the operation of some sort of virtual pseudo-operators, several in Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies publishing their own price lists for mobile telephone services, but the latter are only partially public.
In most cases, there are companies dealing with multi-level marketing.
For example, special mobile telephone services are offered by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The price lists of these firms usually reach only elected ones.
The magic tower consists in the fact that the company does in front of the operator is a classic company client, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, she obtains special price offers (and others).
What is problematic is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such resale.
"If what you're talking about happens, it could be a breach of the contractual conditions that we would examine and that could lead to a cessation of collaboration with the company in question," answered our question about this problem Martina Kemrová.
However, it is quite unlikely that an echo of such an activity would have reached the managers of mobile operators.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned, there may be thousands of customers.
An operator, however, does not rule against such a procedure.
Indeed, the activities of these companies bring them non-negligible benefits, and at the same time, as opposed to real virtual operators, they do not threaten them at all with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický indicates the possible problems: "The law allows such speculations, however, the services of these companies are only used by a negligible percentage of customers.
In addition, they are forced to admit that the SIM card in their phone is not registered under their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it, in the manner of ordinary mobile operators' customers."
This is precisely what should seem strange at the ČTU.
In addition, another question is asked to UOHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes to such a procedure, why are they blocking the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the UOHS has relatively broad powers to be able to disclose such an activity, and if it does not wish to be satisfied with the explanations of the operators, who claim to have no idea that this would happen, their contractual conditions prohibit it.
When we are no longer the most expensive country
As we have already mentioned on several occasions, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has led to a considerable fall in the price of services.
However, in virtually all countries where virtual operators appeared, conventional operators were trying, sometimes more, sometimes less, to prevent their creation.
The arguments used by the latter were almost the same - a market too small or even too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
It was precisely at this level that regulators in developed countries had intervened, not in the interests of mobile operators, but in the interests of their customers.
Both formal and informal measures have led to the creation of a first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies deal with this issue in the manner of a hot potato that is removed by transmitting it to a nearby target.
As a result of the experiences we have, we cannot get rid of the impression that confusion in skills is in these cases more than profitable.
But let's not throw the handle after the banging.
If the sliding information is true and a virtual operator will soon appear at our home, the Czech mobile market may be back in motion.
If one of the operators has accepted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, the UOHS will hardly be able to remain impatient with the rejection (discrimination) of other stakeholders.
And perhaps we will stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four achievements of the new version of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, on the occasion of the Czech Citizenship Day, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek solemnly presented the new recordings of the national anthem Kde Domov můj (Where is my homeland?).
The anthem was again recorded by the orchestra of the National Theatre under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
We have four versions - with a male or female solo song, an interpretation with chorus and an instrumental version.
The song is performed by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček are the authors of the anthem's arrangements.
You can listen to the four new versions on the iHNed.cz server.
Bělohlávek regards Czech national singing as one of the most beautiful hymns.
As he had previously told Český rozhlas (Czech public radio), he chose to interpret the solo versions of singers with young and representative voices, which are marked and appreciated.
"From the beginning, I tried to take care that both singers, as well as the choir, had a good diction, so that we could understand the words, that they sing simultaneously," he said.
The Czech national anthem will celebrate its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Kde domov mūj played for the first time in 1834 on the boards of Stavovské divadlo (the Theatre of the States) in Fidlovačka (Kermesse of the Saveters), an original Czech piece by Josef Kajetán Tyl, accompanied by the music of František Škroup.
It became popular and people spontaneously appropriated it.
After the creation of Czechoslovakia in 1918, the first couplet naturally became an integral part of the national anthem.
It remained one of the seven national symbols even after the creation of the independent Czech Republic.
