The Swedes were demanding a referendum in the USA
The Germans of the Sudeten asked in 1945 for Šumava to be integrated into the United States.
This stems from a letter deposited in the collections of the Jihočeská vědecká knihovna (The Scientific Library of the South Bohemian).
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, at least we want to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
In 1945, certain groups of Germans of the Sudeten allegedly addressed the president of the USA with such a desire.
This stems, among other things, from a preserved letter in a private archive, which is now deposited in the collections of the Jihočeská vědecká knihovna.
Germans from Český Krumlov ask in the letter the American president not to allow "šumavská župa" (forest region south of Bohemian) - annexed by Hitler under the Munich agreement - to be returned to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation and want to be truly certain that the words proclaiming that American troops come to German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," is written in the letter, signed "People, to whom the fate of Šumava is dear."
Since the alliance with Czechoslovakia is supposedly promising - knowing the Czech national character - only of brutality, attitude without regard, misunderstanding, oppression and servitude, the authors of the letter ask the American President to take into his hands the protectorate of Šumava for now and forever.
"We cannot believe that you would give this territory to a foreign state that oppresses and destroys minorities and that in no way has contributed to the victory of the Allies without taking into account the opinion of the quarter of a million inhabitants," is written in the letter.
The alleged reason why the authors cannot sign the letter is the fear of the desire for revenge of "Czech oppressors".
If the president of the United States doubted the opinion of the Germans of Šumava, he would have to organize, according to the authors of the letter, a referendum in the region to establish whether his inhabitants wanted to be part of the United States, or to live under the patronage of the United States.
Although the text contained in the letter may, given the current knowledge of the post-war history, seem somewhat naive, according to some survivors, it illustrates well the expectations of the Germans of the Swedes of the time.
While the Czech Germans had to at least imagine that the question of their expulsion from the republic would arise, very few of them admitted such a possibility.
Some expected the United States and Britain to gain some kind of autonomy for the Swedes.
Others believed that they would simply remain in Czechoslovakia.
The famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, born in České Budějovice, confirms this.
During the war, he was, as German of České Budějovice, engaged in the navy in the Baltic countries.
When at the end of the war he was captured by the English and placed in the capture camp of the Holstein region, dozens of Czech Germans came to consult him to teach them the Czech.
"They believed that once they returned home, the Czech would benefit them," said Chalupa.
None of the captured Germans who lived in Czechoslovakia before the war believed that, following the Beneš Decrees, he would be expelled from the republic.
