Rats also have sensations
A rat or a cockroach runs away from danger, does that mean he also feels scared?
Neurophysicist Joseph LeDoux is convinced of this: many animals also have sensations.
But how can we verify that he feels the same way when he behaves in the same way as we do?
In the online magazine "Edge", contributions have been published for several years by famous scientists.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents in a series of articles the answers to the question "What do you think is true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have feelings and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else having so far been able to prove it just as we cannot prove that other human beings have a consciousness.
But in this case, at least one can hope that all human brains present the same configuration.
As soon as we turn to other species and approach the questions of the feeling or in general of consciousness, we will enter hard-to-practice terrain because the Hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, he does the same thing as many other animals: he does death, flees or attacks.
Human beings behave in the same way, which is why some scientists deduce a comparable subjective experience.
But I don't believe it.
Two aspects of brain structure make the transposition of our subjective experience to that of animals difficult.
One aspect is that the circuits associated almost always with human consciousness include the lateral prefrontal Cortex (because of its participation in the short-term memory and in the functions of direction and execution).
This vast region is much more developed in humans than in other primates and seems to be entirely absent in other beings.
All the less so for these aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal Cortex, among which the consciousness of who we are, and the ability to predict and decide, it is reasonable to assume that the human being is even different from the other primates.
Another significant feature could be the linguistic nature of Man: a large part of his existence is related to language, which often means that his consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if the consciousness was not to depend on the language, it would surely influence it, so that the animal consciousness, whatever the way it is produced, would probably differentiate much from most of our states of consciousness.
That is why it is also difficult to determine what consciousness can look like in other animals.
