Talk while sleeping
Some kids talk at night.
I am not referring to those who wake up very awake telling us something that happened the day before, but to the children who speak during their sleep.
The first time this happens may surprise you, but it doesn't really matter.
It is a benign alteration of sleep called drowsiness.
This is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure there's more than one talking at night.
This phenomenon can appear in a very sporadic way (for example, once in life associated with a high fever episode), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once a month...), the day according to the child no longer remembers anything.
There is no single cause that determines its appearance
They are often linked to other sleep impairments such as nightmares, night terrors, night enuresis (piping in bed) or sleepwalking, but this is not always the case.
As we have already said before, they can also be associated with very high fevers, stress or overexcitation situations.
Anyway, it's a little studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it occurs is also very variable.
He may speak with a quiet little voice, with isolated words, murmurs or on the contrary with cries, tears, long speeches ...
If somniloquia becomes very common, it would be wise to observe the child and consult a specialist, to check if there is a problem that causes a lot of anxiety and to obtain an explanation for this problem.
We said it's a benign alteration, which is why there is no treatment, unless it's related to another sleep alteration that can be treated (for example, if it's related to sleep apnea or stress).
What can be done is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child before going to sleep.
So look for quiet games and avoid programs or TV series that are more or less violent.
With very nervous children who have difficulty relaxing, relaxation techniques can be used to help them calm down inside.
This will allow the child to have a more peaceful sleep.
As soon as the sleepyloquies appear, try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will no longer remember what happened.
Useful advice
Don't wake him up.
It's useless because he's unconscious and you'd wake him up.
Even if he speaks, he sleeps and then rests.
Remember that if it is very distressed several times, it is advisable to consult a doctor or check what causes so much anxiety in the child.
If you understand what he says (which is not usual), do not have the temptation to question him for information.
You won't get anything, because by sleeping, he's not conscious to be able to organize his thinking.
In addition, you will hear what he says, but you won't know what he's dreaming about, so be careful how you interpret the information and the conclusions you draw from it.
Never tell the child that you can interview him at night to know his secrets.
Not even by joking.
This causes a lot of anxiety.
In conclusion, don't worry, it's nothing bad, it's an episode that only lasts a few minutes.
