Sarkozy to meet angry fishermen
Before flying to the United States, Nicolas Sarkozy will make a detour through Brittany.
Faced with the demonstration of force of the fishermen who strongly disrupted on Monday the access of several Breton and Norman ports, the President of the Republic decided to visit the port of Guilvinec, in Finistère, on Tuesday morning, to meet their representatives.
They promised to welcome him "in a constructive spirit" and hope that he "will come with concrete proposals".
A presidential visit which falls at the same time as a general meeting of the "crisis committee" created by the Breton fishermen to obtain measures in the face of the flight of gas prices, which reached a record of more than 1.14 euros per litre on average.
According to the spokesman for Elysée David Martinon, the president "will discuss with them solutions that can be imagined to help their businesses regain competitiveness and to secure the conditions of employment and compensation of sailors".
Nicolas Sarkozy is expected on a firm foot by the fishermen.
On Tuesday morning, they carried out snail operations in Morbihan and Calvados, causing closures of nearly 10 km.
Quiberon's marina was also blocked, but links to Belle-île were not stopped.
A filter dam was set up on the Quiberon peninsula.
The sailors have already shown their determination on Monday by burning tires and pallets in front of the fuel deposits of the ports of Brest, and Lorient, while demonstrations were taking place in Concarneau or Saint-Brieuc.
The movement has spread to other ports of the Atlantic façade and the Channel, such as the Sables d'Olonne, in Vendée, where trawlers have stayed at dock, or in Havre, where about 20 ships have blocked the movements of commercial ships.
The fishermen of La Turballe and the Croisic, in the Loire-Atlantique, stopped in the evening the blockade of the important refinery Total de Donges.
Those of Boulogne-sur-Mer decided to wait for the meeting to be held on Wednesday in the ministry to decide on possible actions.
In Guilvinec, the "crisis committee" must decide on Tuesday on the follow-up to the movement and its participation in the interview scheduled for the Ministry of Agriculture and Fisheries in Paris.
But some Breton fishermen do not want to be represented by officials of the National Fisheries Committee, who did not support their movement.
"The strike will continue" because "fishers will not let go" and "they will not want to move to Paris," said Liliane Cariou, president of the Lorient Fisheries Committee, for example.
Professional fishermen, who do not pay taxes on diesel, currently pay about 50 cents per litre, but believe that the profitability threshold of a vessel is only reached with a diesel less than €0.30 per litre.
