The interview - Blood became safe again
Hema-Québec celebrated yesterday the 10th anniversary of its foundation, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, was right to rejoice, as Hema-Québec became one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And above all, he regained the confidence of the public that had been seriously shaken by the scandal of contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, national blood supplies managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were contaminated with acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In February 1994, the Government of Canada launched a public inquiry, chaired by Justice Horace Krever, to shed light on the circumstances leading to such a tragedy and to make recommendations for such a disaster to cease.
While Justice Krever was late in filing his report, some provinces then set up a committee to plan for a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this mandate.
Following the Gelineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Hema-Québec to serve Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and territories.
"In 1998, when Hema-Québec began its activities, barely 38% of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec," recalls Dr. Decary.
The situation was discouraging.
With efforts to improve the safety of blood and work products on the ground during the years that followed, we regained public confidence," she said before proudly affirming that at the beginning of 2008, nearly 94% of Quebec's population now had confidence in Hema-Québec.
Dr. Décary, however, keeps in mind that "trust is something extremely fragile".
Since its creation, on September 28, 1998, Hema-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, many cases of the human form of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, were seen in Europe, the one that has held the fort since its founding in 1998.
"And we did not know at all whether this disease could be transmitted by blood.
One of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports was that when it is not known and a serious disease can result from it, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by brain degeneration leading inevitably to death, exclusion measures are introduced.
In April 1999, the blood of those who had spent more than a month in the United Kingdom since 1980 was refused.
A few years ago, however, it has been shown beyond doubt that this disease is transmitted by blood.
This episode has thus shown us that the precautionary principle that has been applied has meaning."
In 1999, a much more sensitive technique for HIV testing appeared on the market: the nucleic acid (NAT) tests, which allow the presence of the virus itself in the blood of donors and not the presence of antibodies against the virus, on which the tests used until then were based.
TANs have been able to shorten the silent period, which extends from the time the person was infected to the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
This period could be reduced to less than one week.
This substantially reduced the risk that some donors would be infected without knowledge and could not be detected.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS through blood transfusions.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV-contaminated blood.
"In other words, this means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone gets infected with HIV.
As Hema-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of transmission of HIV by a blood product occurs.
I believe that today we can feel comfortable receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover health," says the Chief Executive Officer of Hema-Québec.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
We never know which pathogen will emerge in the system.
No later than last year the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
It is necessary to be constantly vigilant," says Dr. Décary before pointing out that in addition to a secure supply, Héma-Québec must also provide sufficient supply.
"Needs increase because the population ages.
Since anticancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need recharge in red blood cells or platelets.
The aging population also has consequences on the blood donor network, which averages only 3% of Quebecers eligible for blood donation."
Any healthy person aged 18 years and over who meets the eligibility criteria may still give blood every 56 days, six times a year.
On average, 14 per cent of people who offer their blood are not accepted, because they suffer from AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have travelled to a country where malaria occurs, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
"With these 3%, we manage to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Shortages are very rare.
But it is necessary to renew the members of this donor network as they age and can no longer give their blood.
It is difficult to convince people to give their blood, but above all to hold them back and encourage them to become a regular donor.
Today's life is so frightening, we rarely find time to spend an hour giving blood," says Francine Decary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Québec provides not only blood products, but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eye globes and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Héma-Québec, which also manages the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was once considered a biomedical waste is filled with blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the banking of our thousandth sample of cord blood and we plan to collect more than a thousand of it a year.
We should start proposing for transplants at the beginning of next year," says Dr. Decary, who describes this blood collection program as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed to be unable to access it," as Héma-Québec has no means to offer this complex and costly program in all hospitals in Quebec.
