Free opinion - Barrick Gold's Orwellian Speech
In its September 17 edition, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, Vice-President Director of Canadian Mining Barrick Gold.
Following an Orwellian logic, he claims that the largest gold company in the world has initiated a defamation suit of six million against three authors and a small publishing house without money in order to launch a "transparent public debate".
While it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth that they judge, especially in the case of defamation proceedings, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, this fundamental difference is completely obscured by Mr. Garver.
Because, for Barrick Gold, would the best way to conduct a public debate be to ruin anyone who dares to support a position contrary to his own?
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the authors and the publisher of the Black Canada book will have to spend considerable sums to prepare their defence and to fight, with very unequal arms, against an army of lawyers backed by almost no-bottom pockets of mining.
The tactics, in these unequal struggles, are often to ruin the defendants in order to impose a friendly settlement that will stun the opposition in addition to scaring anyone who dares to look back at the issue.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it was before the public that she should have presented her vision of the facts.
Contrary to what is being done in many of the countries where Barrick Gold works, discussions in Canada are normally conducted through the exchange of ideas and not by beatings.
It was therefore sufficient for mining to open its books, its records and to establish a real debate, through newspapers, the media, publications and the financing of independent research teams that could have shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold seems not to trust public opinion and rejects from the back of his hand the petitions and letters of support to Black Canada's authors.
Perhaps Mr Garver could explain how he can both ask for a "public" debate while ignoring the views of the same public?
In the vice-president's world, it seems that this word refers only to paid and not to all Canadians; this is a rather narrow view of the concept.
In democracy, even detractors have the right to speak.
What does not understand - or does not want to understand - Barrick Gold is that the public that supports Black Canada's authors and publishers does so primarily because it rejects the brutal manner of mining.
This public is ready to hear Barrick and judge, but on the basis of civilized exchanges of arguments, and not in the context of what many perceive as a barbell chase (following the "public debate", Barrick Gold has just filed a statement against Black Canada's authors urging them to stop using this term...).
Beyond Mr. Garver's surreal speech, the pursuit of Barrick Gold is a direct attack on the freedom of academic research and the quest for truth, essential to any democratic society.
It denies, in block, the right to quote credible sources and to debate facts and interpretations, which are the very basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and discuss topics that displease the rich businesses of this world in a country like Canada, under penalty of repeated prosecution, who will be able to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, she could do so by following the scientific standards used by Black Canada's authors.
She has a right of reply.
The academic community, to which we belong, has long known how to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's disproportionate pursuit clearly shows that, contrary to what she claims, she has no desire for a transparent debate.
It is a loss to the academic world, as well as to the public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place devices that limit this type of abusive prosecution.
Wall Street Rescue Operation - Democrats and Republicans Agree
The Bush administration and the leaders of Congress, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the largest economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the $700 billion plan to curb the financial crisis that has shaken Wall Street for months still needs to be endorsed by both Congress chambers.
In particular, it provides for: improved control by the elected officials of its implementation, new mechanisms to ensure the reimbursement of the public money committed, new provisions to contain the number of houses seized for default, and a right to look at wages paid to the managers of the assisted enterprises.
The U.S. Treasury Secretary, Henry Paulson, Speaker of the House of Representatives, Nancy Pelosi, and the Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight yesterday after a two-day marathon.
"We have made great progress towards an agreement that will be effective in the markets," said Bush administration representative Henry Paulson.
"Everything has been done to protect the real economy and ordinary Americans from the ongoing crisis on Wall Street," the Democrat explained.
"This is the fundamental point: if we don't do this, trauma, chaos and disruptions to the daily lives of Americans will be immense," Republican Judd Gregg said.
The negotiations had turned to sprint in the last few hours for fear of the effect of a new failure on the mood of investors.
The time limit that had been agreed was the opening of the markets this morning.
Lately associated with the negotiations, the two candidates for the U.S. presidential election were rather in favour of the agreement, but without failing to express their dissatisfaction with the fact that they were forced to reach that end.
Senator Barack Obama attributed himself to the addition of certain provisions to the agreement, including the provision to allow the owners to keep their homes and the addition of the salary of the leaders of the companies rescued by the state.
"When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of some, there is nothing to be congratulated for.
But these measures are necessary," he commented on the waves of American television.
Asked on another channel to see if he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, replied: "I'd like to see the details, but I hope so."
"The broad lines I have read [show] that this is something that we will all have to digest and with which we will be able to move forward.
The option of doing nothing is simply not acceptable," he said.
The $700 billion plan aims to buy back with taxpayers' money the doubtful, risky and unsold debts of US financial institutions.
It comes after 14 months of a crisis triggered by the bursting of a real estate bubble that first led to the collapse of mortgages at risk (subprimes) before extending to other more widespread forms of credit securities (PCAA) and leading to a liquidity freeze and the debandade of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of Republicans who had the first draft agreement overturned last week.
It is believed that they have come out of this impasse since the Democrats accepted that certain "toxic" assets of companies in difficulty are only insured by the government, rather than purchased.
In order to round the angles for everyone in Congress, it was also added a provision stipulating that if the government were to incur losses for five years with this program, it could put in place new taxes to help it recover its bet.
The new plan provides for a first tranche of 250 billion to be paid in addition to another 100 billion if the President deems it necessary.
Another 350 billion is expected to be approved by another Congressional vote.
In exchange for his help, Washington will get a stake in the rescued companies that will be worth dividends in the event of profit and that he will be able to resell when the torment is over.
The federal government will be given the opportunity to delay the seizure procedures for housing for the real estate loans affected by this plan, as well as to set limits on compensation and severance benefits paid to the managers of the affected companies.
The plan's architects would like to see it submitted to the House of Representatives today and to the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all their efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will have the green light.
Indeed, votes continued to rise yesterday against this project, both in the Republican and Democratic camp.
"Obviously, Washington doesn't hear you," said Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the Chamber's Finance Committee, at the address of his constituents.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But not the one that involves taking advantage of taxpayers."
Moderator of a small group at the Congress called "the caucus of skeptics", Democratic representative Brad Sherman presents things differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
"Four hundred eminent economic professors, including three Nobel Prize winners, wrote to us to tell us: Congress is asked not to rush and to examine carefully the way forward," he said yesterday.
At the same time, in Europe, we once again had proof of the global nature of the crisis.
At the end of an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalisation of the Fortis banking group for EUR 11.2 billion (16.3 billion US).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg had been made necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it had given up acquiring its competitors in full sinking since it lost 2 billion euros (US$ 2.9 billion) in the crisis of risk real estate loans in the United States.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is one of the twenty largest European banks and ten largest insurers.
"This is not lost money," said Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos yesterday.
In return, you get a right to vote in the bank and influence.
It is precisely something that savers and households now appreciate that times are uncertain."
Meanwhile, on the other side of the Channel, the British government seemed to be in the process of nationalizing another bank under the influence of the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government would resume all outstanding loans at Bradford and Bringley Bank, including more than US$41 billion (US$75.5 billion) of real estate loans.
The Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that it would buy the branches and customer accounts of the British bank.
Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank, after Northern Rock, to be nationalized by the British government since the beginning of this financial crisis.
