What could Zuschlag &amp; Company do in their invoice factory?
Next, on 8 October, hearings on the current criminal proceedings will begin against János Zuschlag and his accomplices.
The politician and his accomplices are accused of fraud, in the form of a criminal organization, on a permanent and regular basis, resulting in particularly significant damage, and other charges have been brought against them, such as falsehood and use of falsehood.
According to the Public Prosecutor's Office, the money from grants was spent for personal purposes, while the benefits were justified by false invoices.
The money of the State and the municipalities, about 65 million HUF in total, went on the one hand in the caisses of the Fial Baloldal movement and on the other, in the pocket of some people.
Their method, also made public by the investigating authorities, was to receive the money from the subsidies obtained by issuing bills of fees, after which no actual benefit was provided and thus, the associations never complied with their commitments.
According to the indictment, a large part of the invoices were false.
For the latter, they obtained bill books at the Józsefváros market, while manufacturing the stamps in Kiskunhalas.
For the names of companies that would appear on the invoices, it was decided, among other things, on tours in the northern province of Lake Balaton, carried out by István Lados, at the request of János Zuschlag.
According to the latter's testimony, he had to find pensions and restaurants.
For his personal consumption, he asked for an invoice, on the basis of which they made the other invoices that they would introduce, among other things, to the Ministry of Youth and Sports, the Ministry of Social Affairs and Labour, as well as the Municipality of the Capital to access subsidies.
The majority of the invoices were created by István Lados and his accomplice András Łri, who, according to our information, was mainly concerned with drafting the files necessary to obtain the grants.
During a "tracking circuit", one of Lados' choices was a bistro.
According to the two invoices issued by the Zuschlag in 2003, this place ensured the restoration of a group of 90 people, members of the association Biztos Pont Egyesület.
However, according to the manager, it would have been impossible for so many people to occupy this place at the same time.
In the same way, in the summer of 2002, the invoice drawn up on behalf of the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, which will later bear the name of Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért, sprang from faults of form and substance.
A pension, located in Badacsonytomaj, actually had only three bedrooms, and a maximum of ten people could spend the night there. However, the bill mentioned one hundred and thirty customers.
In addition, the over-imagination bill issuers fell into excess when they mentioned the company Pigal Kft, also belonging to the Horeca sector. In their accounts, neither the name Jobb Jövőért nor the name of Hoppá appeared, according to the information given to the prosecutor.
Győző Farkas, the company's manager, told hvg.hu that when the prosecutor summoned him and showed him the invoices, he immediately knew that they were false documents.
"The name of our company and our tax number were placed in a bad place on the stamp."
He added: "Beyond the shape, the fact that according to the bill, one hundred people stayed there, also did not collate, since this establishment counts only eleven rooms, which do not have as much space.
In addition, the bill also mentions meals, and our restaurant has been closed for a long time."
The issuers of zealous invoices also did not find out about the travel agencies in Budapest, which were part of their choice, but only organizing trips abroad. Thus, naively, they indicated stays in Hungary on bills to be paid in cash, which also goes against the agency's accounting practices.
Moreover, as it appeared in the investigation, they also added VAT on these documents, while the travel services, whose destination is outside the European Union, are charged without VAT.
Similarly, the VAT rate of the four invoices established on behalf of the Hôtel Révfülöp in the order of Jobb Jövőért was incorrect, since the company's services did not bear a VAT of 25% as indicated, but a VAT of 15%. Moreover, the hotel employees only issued printed invoices, while the counterfeits were handwritten.
The prosecution's investigation revealed that the "issuers" also made mistakes by mentioning as a service the carriage of goods by road, that the invoice company could not exercise, since its profile was the investment council.
Moreover, it is also for defects of forms, such as inadequate types of invoices and false stamps, that the invoices issued to the order of Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, of XXI. Századi Kulturrális Egyesület and Biztos Pont proved false.
As in the case of Ravenna Bt. or Kunfehertó's sports internship, both of which deny being the authors of the invoices issued on their behalf.
Nor did the counterfeiters pay attention to the fact that the company HIB Kft., established in Nyíregyháza, was in liquidation at the time (in 2001) the group of Fiatal Városért Egyesület was supposed to have a meal at their home. According to our information, that is why the liquidator of the company denies having issued this invoice.
Deliberately established invoices
Another category of invoice issuers is that composed of those who were fully aware that they were being asked to issue fictitious invoices.
The Esély Budapestért Alapítvány Foundation, at the request of the group of Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták, has established an invoice to the order of the Együtt Foundation in Harmadik Évezredért, for a sum of four million HUF.
According to the indictment, the manager of Collab Kft. was forced to issue false invoices by one of the defendants, Ludovic Györfi.
Similarly, it cooperated with the Zuschlags, the company Biogate Kft., which is currently under liquidation and which in 2003 issued invoices to the order of the foundation Jobb Jövőért Alapítvány, the association Atlasz Egyesület and the association Vörösfenyő Egyesület, for an amount of approximately five million HUF, but after which no performance was actually provided.
No financial movement took place, either, since the invoices issued were subsequently cancelled, but that, the agencies did not mention it in their accounts.
The following category of companies issuing invoices is that of companies directly related to the accused.
For example, the administrative delegate of the CEO of Delta Trió Kft., dealing with the fuel and motor vehicle trade, whose head office was in Budapest, but where it was not possible to find it, was Iván Kubatov.
In October, November and December 2005, the company issued several invoices for the sale of computer equipment, amounting to approximately 18 million HUF.
According to the investigation, these equipments were allegedly purchased by Cash Investment Kft. of Kiskunhalas, which had been in liquidation since September 14, 2005.
The director of this company was a man of Romanian origin, to whom Ivan Kubatov would also have sent documents related to the company, between 2002 and 2005.
According to what we know, Kubatov acknowledged during the investigation that he issued invoices to Atlasz, Hoppá and Együtt companies in Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, and that he seized their countervalue.
It was precisely at the request of Ivan Kubatov that Romanian masons created Fa-Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and Jos-Investment Bt.
In fact, none of these companies worked, which the accused explained by the fact that they did not receive work.
He still used these companies, since at the request of Master Zsolt Szente, co-accused as well as editor of the founding acts of the companies, he made invoices to their names, to the order of associations related to Zuschlag, such as the Atlasz and Y-Generáció associations.
Kubatov has given organizations, 15 invoices in total, issued by Cash Investment, Delta Trió, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade, for a value of 14.2 million HUF.
The prosecution thought that 10% of the amounts indicated on the invoices as well as VAT went into Kubatov's pocket.
The man even used the company Szi-Beri Bt. to establish fictitious invoices that were used as part of Biztos Pont's grant application.
In January 2006, the Y-Generáció and Szövetség Association in Modern Magyarországert submitted a request for a subsidy to the public utility body of the Socialist Party, Tancsics Mihály Alapitvány (TMA).
They have obtained this grant twice as much as 500,000 HUF, but these amounts have not been used for the objectives set out in the application.
To avoid this, five fictitious invoices received from Works Team Kft. were presented to the TMA.
Moreover, these invoices were found during the search carried out in the office of Árpád Kemecsei, at the Ministry of Education.
At the hearing, some of the accused will report the method of making invoices, as it had already done before the prosecutor's office.
What could be really interesting would be that the main accused, János Zuschlag himself, decides to lift the veil over the whole story.
So far, his confessions are not very detailed, and although he has repeatedly promised to tell the slightest details, he has not yet done so.
The question is whether it is in his interest, or perhaps the Socialists would have concluded an agreement that in exchange for the reimbursement of a large part of the fifty million HUF, Zusi would carry the hat alone.
Today, the latter is probably vexed, since the requests for his placement in supervised residence, on the basis of a relief from his conditions of detention, fall continuously into the ear of a deaf person.
While those who have caused much greater damage, and those who commit non-reparable economic crimes, walk freely or at least, wait at their own home for the end of the proceedings, he does not have that possibility.
The psychology of the auction: why do we spend more money?
In auction sales, buyers tend to spend more, and overestimate the goods.
Researchers in neurology and economics at the University of New York have been able to update the neurological and economic bases of this known and apparently irrational behavior.
According to their study published in the journal Science, human beings do not want to be distanced during this type of competition, such as an auction on eBay, and that is why they even prefer to pay too high a price.
This research has attempted to develop a neurological pattern of this type of "game" using experimental auction sales.
One of the volunteer groups played the lotus, while the other group took part in a play auction, while using a functional magnetic resonance (FMRI) process, researchers analyzed the active brain domains of experimental subjects.
In both games, participants could earn money, but during the auction, one of the essential elements of which is a third party's auction, the whole under the brain stem, called stratum, was moving intensively during the loss of the party.
This part of the brain, next to several other functions, plays a role in the "self-stimulation" mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, according to the researchers, the rise in prices is explained by the flight to the violent reaction of the stratum.
In support of their theories, economists from this group of researchers continued financial monitoring analyses.
In these cases, three groups were overburdened by a partner under various circumstances.
They simply informed the control group of the actual value of the product in question, and thus carried out their placement.
To another group, they promised that if, in addition, they would win the game, then they would receive an additional $15 as a reward.
While the third group received these $15 before the auction, the group members also lost that money in case they lost the auction.
The difference between these two groups is in fact that the emphasis was on victory, while on failure.
By thus proving the hypothesis of neurologists, the members of the team of players "against failure" were willing to higher bets than those made by the control group and the group "for victory".
"These results cannot be demonstrated by any existing economic theory.
In fact, each one explained the phenomena found in auction sales only by the pleasure of winning and the parade in front of the risk.
Only the methods of neurological imaging have helped to remove the contradiction between the two theories, leading, now, to a third explanation." - found Andrew Schotter, the professor of the Faculty of Economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should we consult a doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary, chronic liver disease is mentioned as one of the first causes of death.
An estimated one hundred thousand patients with hepatitis virus in Hungary, but only seven miles are treated because of the fact that patients often do not know that they are carriers of the virus.
Hepatitis is a generic name given to liver infections caused by different viruses.
There are many similarities between their symptoms. Inflammation of the liver and jaundice are characteristic, but pathogens and congenital diseases differ from one another.
Hepatitis viruses, according to pathogenic genes, mainly spread in two forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (e.g., contaminated food or water), hepatitis B, C, D, and other viruses by blood and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal secretion, saliva).
For travellers, it is in any case recommended to be vaccinated against A and B viruses. There is no C vaccine.
Symptoms of hepatitis A occur two to three weeks after consumption of contaminated foods, usually accompanied by poor general condition, weakness, stomach pain and nausea.
Then a visible yellowish develops on the skin and on the white of the eye, the stools become clearer and the urine takes a darker color. The healing can take two to three weeks.
Around the world, one million people die every year from the most serious form of this disease, such as cancer or liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main cause of this is that, according to estimates, only one in ten patients receive medical treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: if not treated, it can lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most patients do not know how to get infected with the virus, because the pathogenic gene is dimly destroying liver cells. In many cases, the first symptoms only appear after 20 to 30 years.
Therefore, early prevention is very important, as well as regular screening tests.
Contamination is much higher than the average among a population of three groups: people who had had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug users and tattoos.
Currently, there are 200 million patients with chronic hepatitis C worldwide.
Since the disease can be detected through a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult your doctor when you see symptoms of unknown origin.
The disease can be cured, if detected in time. The virus can be eradicated from the body, in this way the risk of contagion disappears and the development of cancer is prevented.
September 30 is the World Hepatitis Day, organized for the first time in 2004 by organizations representing patients from all over the world.
Its objective is to draw attention to chronic liver cirrhosis, caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
Does the one who grows in God feel less pain?
According to the results of a recent research, religious belief would function as a sort of analgesic, which would have already contributed to making the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
The British daily Telegraph published an article according to which researchers at the University of Oxford realized an interesting experience by analyzing the level at which belief in God could influence tolerance to human pain.
As part of this experience for the least odd, 12 Catholic believers and so many atheists were subjected to electroshocks, while each of them observed a painting representing the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude much of the suffering.
Thanks to a technique of palpation of the human brain, it was also found that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain responsible for the regulation of pain.
This analysis is the first in a series of experiments, in which academics, scholars, philosophers and theologians participate from different sectors of the university.
More specifically, the experiment takes place in the following way: an instrument emitting sparks and spreading electroshocks is attached to the left hand of the experimental subject.
The researchers asked the participants of the experience to look at two paintings in a sustained way, one being the Virgin Mary painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century and the other, the Lady with the hermine painted by Léonard de Vinci in the 15th century.
The researchers at the origin of this experience hoped that the view of the Virgin Mary evoked a kind of state of faith among the believers, while the choice of Da Vinci's painting, not very different from the first, had its soothing effect.
The experimental subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, and during that time, they received 20 electroshocks in four successive parts, while looking at either religious theme painting or more general theme painting.
The Catholics said that in the sight of the Virgin Mary, they felt as "safe", as someone who "takes care of" and they "quietly, and peace has invaded them".
In view of the painting of religious theme, they reported 12% less pain than when looking at Leonardo's work.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who himself took part in the experiment, believes that the same effects can be achieved with any other strong image, in atheists, provided he finds the appropriate photo.
"We should find an image to which they react very positively, such as a mother or father," said the psychologist.
Tom Wright, Anglican bishop, praised the results of this research.
"The practice of faith should change and in many cases, it actually changes our personality," Wright added.
After these excellent results, there is only the question of what would be the effect on the regulation of the pain of subjects if the believers are shown a Madonna painted by Leonardo or by a painter of the same calibre?
Would the view of a Virgin Mary of better quality lead to better results?
