The smart car mimics the theft of the bourdon
What method would be better for developing technologies that are capable of avoiding an obstacle, if it is not the imitation of an obstacle detector already existing in nature?
Like, for example, bees.
In the amazing project presented at CETEC, taking place in Japan, the buzzing bees gave the strategic idea of departure to engineers at Nissan, to inspire them on how to design the next generation of obstacle detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built a mini robot car, a self-robotized, bio-inspired BR23C system, which it has equipped with bees qualities, the ultimate objective being to encourage the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
During his flights, each bee constitutes his own space, oval shape, which in reality looks very much like our secure protective hull - he explained, during the exhibition, Kazuhhiro Doi, the director of the research and development department and technological public relations of the brand.
The facet eye of the bee plays a primary role, since it is capable of seeing in all directions, at an angle of 300 degrees.
To imitate the functions of the face-to-face eye, engineers have approached the idea of the laser telemeter.
It identifies the obstacles at an angle of 180 degrees and at a distance of 2 meters in front of the BR23C, it evaluates the distances and sends a signal to the microprocessor on board, which turns it into an escape manoeuvre immediately.
The perception of the obstacle takes place in a fraction of a second. Then, the mini robot, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning from a sufficient angle to avoid collision.
Unlike any system currently in existence, this avoidance manoeuvre is entirely instinctively carried out.
"If it wasn't, the mini-auto robot couldn't react quickly enough to avoid the obstacle," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, the director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robotic car project.
It must react instinctively and instantly, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and the most internal layer of the protective envelope, a layer where the collision is considered inevitable for the moment.
This whole process must reflect what the bee does to avoid other bees.
The process must take place at a glance.
Unlike bees, the difference cannot go up, down or diagonally, it can only be of two dimensions, and only in the direction in which the wheels can turn.
In this way, instead of the infinite combinations that bees possess to avoid other bees, in our case, we could only use rotating motion, acceleration and slowing down as maneuvers available to the mini robot
The BR23C uses Lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and have a greater energy concentration, making their lifespan longer than in the Lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, it is the instinctive intelligent reaction that is paramount, not data processing, and even less the ability to store.
This mechanism should treat only a few incoming signals per second, and react to them.
It is not necessary to store them and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers. In this way, it uses only a few dozen kilobytes of continuous memory.
We don't need memory of a giga-byte capacity, or even mega-bytes.
This is the first step towards the design of a technology for instant avoidance. Nissan estimates that this system will be entering serially manufactured cars in the next ten years.
Another application could be its incorporation into the GPS satellite navigation system, so that it can guide the driver to his destination by avoiding obstacles on his way.
