The written version of the plan was made public before the opening of the Asian markets, Sunday evening at 8 p.m., Washington local time (i.e. Monday at 2 a.m., according to the local time of Central Europe), but it did not cause a spectacular rise in scholarships.
On Monday, the House of Representatives will be the first to vote on the bill responding to the name of the 2008 emergency economic stabilization law. Then, its fate will be in the hands of the Senate.
On Saturday evening, President George W. Bush spoke to Pelosi, then the White House also welcomed the news of the agreement.
"We are satisfied with the progress made tonight, and we highly appreciate the efforts of both parties to stabilize our financial markets and to protect our economy," said Tony Fratto, spokesman for the White House.
In addition, the program diverges from the initial proposal made by the Bush administration, which stated that the $700 billion had to be spent in one single time, for the redemption of doubtful credits.
From now on, up to half of the 700 billion sum can be spent. The first 250 billion will be issued immediately after the adoption of the law by Congress, probably Monday. This first sum will be used by the Secretary of the Treasury to buy suspicious claims from banks, while the use of the additional $100 billion will be left to the President's discretion.
The program will be supervised by an independent body, in which the President of the Federal Reserve will also participate.
The spending of the second half of the 700 billion depends on a new Congressional decree.
Under the law, the Treasury Secretariat will be able to put in place a combined strategy: at the same time, it will be able to purchase doubtful claims, mortgages and doubtful mortgages, as well as other types of "toxic" claims.
The department's competent persons stated that redemptions may take place in the course of an auction, but also directly.
The rule gives the companies concerned the opportunity to take part in an insurance program, where the Treasury Secretariat guarantees the tools behind the concerns, for which companies will have paid a premium equivalent to the foreseeable damages.
Henry Paulson stated that the law provides the necessary tools to allocate $700 billion for the urgent needs of the financial system, whether it is the vast buyback of doubtful debts, their insurance, or to avoid the risk of the system leading to the collapse of one or the other important financial institution.
"We will make the necessary arrangements, to be ready for law enforcement, as soon as it is signed," he added.
On the other hand, bank leaders in bad postures and waiting for state aid can expect their severance payments, simply called the overseas golden parachute, to be capped by the government.
Salary caps are only mentioned in specific cases, and limitations depend on how the Treasury Secretariat offers its assistance to the company.
The cap principle means that if the Treasury Secretariat buys back in the context of an auction, they will collect a surplus of tax on the gold parachute, unless the discredited bank president retires.
Directly after the purchase of doubtful receivables, the government will intervene aggressively to ensure that the amount paid to the leaders is not exaggerated.
In order for the image to be complete, it must be added that the existing golden parachutes are not changed. The ceiling only concerns the new contracts, thus motivating participation in the plan.
This is the first time in the history of the United States that legal caps will be in force regarding the additions of the Directors General - commented the chairman of the committee in charge of the financial benefits of the Chamber of Deputies, the Democrat Barney Frank.
In addition, the State obtains a right to acquire shares in the banks taking part in the plan. Thus, the risk of taxpayers decreases, since they can even be won in the case as soon as the economy and with it the saved banks fall back on their legs.
The bill states that in the next five years, the President must introduce to Congress a proposal that will decide on how the losses will be returned to taxpayers, from the financial sector.
On both sides, of course, there were those who expressed their doubts about this plan.
That's not why American citizens sent us, it doesn't protect taxpayers' dollars - California's Republican MP Darrell Issa said.
