Industrial prices continued to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices rose by 0.1 per cent compared to the previous month, and 12.9 per cent compared to August 2007 - reports the Hungarian Central Statistics Office.
Industrial export sales prices increased by 1.1 per cent compared to July 2008, while compared to the previous year, they decreased by 3.9 per cent.
As a result of fluctuations in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 per cent compared to the previous month, and by 3.2 per cent compared to the previous year.
Domestic industrial sales prices rose only to a lesser extent: 0.1 per cent compared to the previous month.
Domestic sales prices in the processing industries were only slightly higher in the range of 0.1 per cent compared to July.
In August 2008, the most significant price increase was observed in the leather and footwear manufacturing sector (2.8 per cent), with first, the manufacture of bags and belts with a monthly increase of 4.6 per cent, then the production of shoes with 2.5 per cent monthly increase.
The higher price level of plastics and chemical raw materials resulted in a substantial monthly increase in the prices of the chemical and product manufacturing sector (1.6 per cent).
The result was a deflation in the oil processing sectors (1.4 per cent), in the manufacturing of machinery and electrical equipment (0.9 per cent), and a minimal increase in the wood processing sector (0.1 per cent).
The prices of paper production, publishing and printing activities have not changed.
The other sectors of the processing industry increased from 0.2 per cent to 0.9 per cent.
In the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors, representing a significant share of domestic industrial operations, prices rose by 0.3 per cent in August, mainly due to the effect of the increase in gas prices established by the authorities since 1 July.
In a 12-month comparison, taking into account the domestic sales of processing sectors, the most significant increase in prices in the oil processing sector (32.4 per cent) was observed.
In the metallurgical manufacturing sector, prices increased by 13.2 per cent, while in the important area of food production, beverages and tobacco, prices increased by 11 per cent.
Price reductions have taken place in the textile and textile production sectors (2.5 per cent), as well as in the manufacturing of electrical machinery and appliances (0.3 per cent).
In other sectors of the processing industry, price increases have changed from 0.6 per cent to 9.1 per cent.
In the processing industry as a whole, prices have increased by 10.2 per cent over the past year.
The prices of the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors exceeded those of the previous year by 18.7 per cent.
Among the domestic trade groups and by sector allocation, in August, the most significant monthly price increase (0.7 per cent) was shown by investment-based profit-initiators.
In the consumer goods production sectors, prices increased by 0.3 per cent, while in the energy and materials sectors for further processing there was no change compared to the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the largest increase in energy and material production was observed for further processing (16.8 per cent).
In consumer goods production sectors, an inflation rate of 6.8 per cent was measured, while for profit-producing sectors, a decrease of 1.4 per cent was measured.
The export prices of the industrial sector in HUF increased by 1.1 per cent in August compared to the previous month, while they fell by 3.9 per cent over 12 months.
In one month, our national payment method has weakened by 1.7 per cent compared to the euro, and by 7.1 per cent against the dollar. Compared to August 2007, it has increased by 7.5 per cent against the euro and by 15.9 per cent against the dollar.
