"A overwhelming majority of young Roma do not have secondary education diplomas, and as a result of poor elementary education, only a tiny part has the possibility of obtaining a higher education diploma."
Furthermore, Járóka stressed that education as a basic human right plays a key role in upholding other fundamental rights.
Investment in the early education of Roma children means strengthening the economy of the European Union member countries.
According to the Euro MP, it is necessary to raise awareness of these relations in the widest possible circle, also between Roma and non-Romans.
In fact, the sooner a Roma child starts school, the more likely he is to become a productive member of the labour market; by taxes paid from his income and consumption, he participates in the state budget.
