Mp3 player pointed at the finger, they put the hearing at risk.
Listening to full volume music for an extended period using portable music devices such as Mp3 players can cause permanent hearing damage.
This is what the European Commission announces, which, in a press release in Brussels, cites the opinion of the Scientific Committee, on the newly identified and unforeseen health risks (Csrseri) of the EU, published today.
"of this scientific report - we read in the note - it appears that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to full volume music using portable musical devices, for more than one hour per day and per week, risk a permanent loss of hearing capacity."
"I am concerned that such a large number of young people who frequently use portable music devices and full-volume mobile phones can unconsciously damage their hearing in an irreparable way," says Meglena Kuneva.
"According to the scientific data - the responsible Ue- continues it is a clear risk and we must react quickly.
The most important thing is to raise consumer awareness and make this information public.
We must also review existing control systems in the light of scientific opinion so that they are fully effective and can monitor new technologies."
Brussels asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the intensive use of portable music devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to noise generated by them.
"The scientists-concluded the executive EU- confirm that there are good reasons to worry, and that the European Commission will now examine with the Member States and other interested parties, what measures could possibly be taken to better protect children and adolescents, against exposure to noise from portable music devices and similar devices.
There is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable music devices to 100Db, but concern is raised about hearing damage that could result from excessive exposure to such noise sources.
It is possible to limit these data well using solutions such as reducing levels and duration of exposure to noise.
The Ue Scientific Committee notes that users of portable music devices, who listen to full volume music (more than 89 decibels) for 5 hours per week, exceed the current limits on the maximum level of noise at the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for prolonged periods risk a permanent loss of hearing capacity after 5 years.
This concerns 5-10% of the users of these devices, and their number can be quantified around 2.5 and 10 million people in the U.S.
Rome, Alemanno gave the order to have the Commission set up for the future of the capital.
Today we begin, in March we finish, in June we will draw the sums.
This is the timetable set by the Capitol for the work of the "Commission for the Future of Rome Capitale", which took place this morning at the new headquarters behind the Caracalla Baths.
In six months, President Antonio Marzano and the 49 other members of the Commission will develop the directives for Rome.
In March, when they are finished, the Committee and the City Council will evaluate the analyses and projects, in order to present in June, the Strategic Plan for Rome with the "official stamp " of the Capitol and its mayor Gianni Alemanno.
"The commission is absolutely independent; all political, social and cultural ideas are represented in it - it wishes to emphasize Alemanno - it will have to propose ideas for development of Rome that can be used by the political decision makers, who remain the Committee and the Communal Council.
No superimposition of roles, but only the desire to have a corner where to develop a great project for Rome.
In March, it will have completed its tasks and will then disappear, as this experience must have a precise temporal duration.
In June the Mayor announced - we will present the strategic plan resulting from the work carried out by the Commission for the future of Rome Capitale. "
For those who accuse the Commission of being useless, since its opinions will not be binding, Alemanno replied: "It all depends on the work that the Commission will be able to do, as well as on the quality of its proposals.
If quality is there, as in France thanks to the Attali Commission, as in Rome, I am sure, its contribution will be fundamental.
Too often the policy is overwhelmed by the management of everyday life and emergencies that occur from time to time.
On the contrary, we want to see forward, and further forward, towards a deeper forward-looking, working seriously for the development of Rome and its future."
Moreover, the Mayor of Rome wishes to stress that "this Commission is not an unnecessary body or a bureaucratic whole: it is absolutely free, and it will not cost the Roman citizens a euro, and it will be used to study and involve the best intelligences that express the Capital.
For Alemanno, in fact, "it takes a strategic reference draft, neither firm nor immobile, in order to enable our city to improve itself, which it absolutely needs, while thinking about its future now a unitary spirit, ".
A future that, the mayor of Rome says, "will not limit itself to the usual communal borders, but that will look further" not only in the perspective of the future metropolitan city and its legal status as Capital, but" also in relation to the role that Rome can and must have, as Capital of Europe and the Mediterranean".
