The super glue to walk on the walls.
To overcome the laws of gravity thanks to a super glue and, in the future, to walk on the walls like Spiderman.
This is the goal of various American research centres, and today, a team of four institutes has almost succeeded.
With an adhesive measuring just 2.5 square centimetres, the researchers managed to hold a body of 100 kilograms on a vertical wall.
STUDY- The American journal Science has published the findings of some researchers from the University of Dayton, Akron, Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material, invented by the team of researchers, is an evolution of those we know who use a particular carbon structure, called nano carbon tubes.
"The glue principle can be imagined as a series of tubes arranged as a spaghetti pile." Explains Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology at Atlanta.
Scientists drew inspiration from the legs of the geckos, covered with microscopic hairs that allow the animal to ensure a perfect adherent.
Tests on various materials, such as glass, Teflon, and glass paper, have shown that the new adhesive is ten times more powerful than the legs of these reptiles, and at the same time, that it "removes easily from the wall" explains Liming Dai, a researcher at the University of Dayton Faculty of Engineering.
MARKING ON DEATHS? –"This material could be used as a temporary adhesive," adds Liming Dai.
Maybe to walk on walls like Spiderman? Maybe so, but researchers think of a much less fascinating use such as the connection between electronic devices, since nano carbon tubes are conductors of heat and electric current.
Other applications may be related to aerospace engineering.
For now, no superhero.
THE OTHER RESEARCH- The University of Berkeley, California, is also dedicated to seeking a new adhesive.
In an article by the American Chemical Society, Californian researchers presented an adhesive made of microfibers like hair, which self-cleans dust during movement on a surface to ensure perfect and constant adhesion.
