Watch out for grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These beverages, consumed mainly in the summer because they are disaltering and rich in vitamins, if associated with certain vital medicines, alter the absorption amplifying or decreasing, depending on the case, their effectiveness, with even serious consequences for health.
David Nailey, professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, recalls the risks of fruit juices, whether in box or fresh, if associated with the ingestion of certain drugs; during the 236th National Meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia, he launched a new alarm: just a glass of grapefruit juice, orange and apples, to reduce the absorption of certain vital drugs, cancelling their beneficial effects and endangering the health of patients.
Grapefruit juice has already been heavily criticized because it has been held responsible for increasing the effects of certain anti-arrhythmic, antibiotic, anxiolytic, anti-stamine and neurological drugs to toxic levels.
DRUGS A RISK- It was the Italian Medicines Agency itself, which had given the news in a two-year newsletter, alerting doctors and patients not to under-estimate the danger of this mixture and to pay attention to what they drink, if they take medicines such as Diazépam or Methadone.
NOT THAT PAMPLEMOUSSE- According to experts, even orange and apple juice contains substances that inhibit drugs.
Long is the list of active substances inhibited by grapefruit and other juices.
