Student victims of expensive rents, up to 900 euros for a room.
Student rental market doesn't know a crisis
According to the latest investigation by the Sunia, the tenants' union, renting a single room can cost a student, up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples, 600 in Rome.
"The phenomenon has now reached very serious aspects to the point of excluding entire categories of young people, from the right to study because of the very high overall costs that the families of origin must support- explains the head of the study office of Sunia, Laura Mariani- in these cities, the high demand on the part of the students has so distorted the market that a process of general increase has begun even for the residents.
In most cases, rental offers also involve a series of violations: free-type contracts, unregistered contracts, no rent limit, sub-locations.
For the Sunia, extraordinary interventions through the revision of tax taxation are necessary to calm the prices.
Reading in detail the survey, we see that in Milan, for a bed in the Brianza area, it takes about 450 euros; for a single room, it goes from 650 euros minimum (Black Band area), to an average value of 800 (Lambiate, Udine, and Fiera area) to a maximum of 900 euros (Vittoria area)
In Florence, one bed costs on average, 350/400 euros, one room about 700 euros.
In Bologna, where students concentrate in areas close to the University, it takes 250/280 euros for a bed in a double bed, and from 370 to 500 for a single room.
In Rome, in the areas close to the central universities (San Lorenzo, Piazza Bologna), we ask about 600 euros for a simple one, 450 for a bed in a double one.
A slightly lower value (550 euro for a single one) for areas close to other universities (Ostiense and Cinecittà).
You can save only if you step away in the peripheral areas: 300 euros for a bed, and 450 for a single one in the Predestina, Centocelle or similar area.
In Naples, for a bed it takes 300/400 euros, for a simple one, we spend 400 to 600 euros, with higher prices in the zones Policlinico, Vomero, and Colli Aminei.
In Bari, for a bed, you have to count 250/350 euros, at least 350 euros for a simple one.
In smaller cities, prices are lower in absolute terms, but they are of major importance in the urban economy.
Finally, cities such as Perugia, in which rents are often taken by extra community students, there is a subsequent anomaly: the rent applied to foreign students is increased by 25/30 % compared to that applied to Italians.
Farewell old cinema Paradiso, cities eliminate historic halls.
Historical cinemas close in favor of the Multiplexs.
"A city without cinemas is a blind city, it's like a face without eyes"
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore, illustrates well what is happening in the major Italian urban centers, but also in the cities of province,
The process of marginalisation of cinemas, with the birth on the periphery of the large multi-salles, and the death of consumption of mono-salles in the central areas of the cities, is one of the major events that seems inevitable and indisputable; it also has all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
To disappear, they are often historical places and charged with memory, "it is as if one of my friends disappeared, someone we know, with whom we shared a bit of a path and so many emotions" observes the director of the New Cinema Paradiso, a film that offers to Tornatore 20 years ago, the first Oscar and the Grand Prix of the jury of Cannes, and that told the poetry of a provincial hall, and the nostalgia of a way to live the cinema, lost can be forever.
The figures provided by Anec, the main association of merchants, mean everything: in the last five years, 316 traditional cinemas have closed, and it is the halls of the main cities that paid mainly the costs: 10 less in Florence, 9 less in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 less in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closure, Emilia Romaine is in the lead with 82 mono cinemas lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
The evidence that confirms that the first responsible for their disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, because it is the three Italian regions that have recorded the most new multisalle cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany as in Emilia-Romagna.
"Italian exploitation has developed irrationally" notes Paolo Protti, president of the Anec, "it is useful to build new structures, but it would still be necessary to guarantee the survival of those that already exist, because when a firm room in a city, these frequenters are not necessarily all willing to go to multiplexes.
Not to mention the lack of deliberation of credit for traders: the historical debt of the state is about 10 million euros.
It is shameful that, from an ethical and moral point of view, the Government does not respect existing laws.
To support the sector, it would take between €16 million and €18 million per year.
Note the case of Bologna, the first Italian city, which, concerned about these closures, decided to resolve the situation by signing a protocol between Mairie and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy, to defend and promote mono-room cinemas in historical and peripheral centres.
Among the regulations provided for, there are measures of tax facilities for managers and benefits to the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the restricted area, and will have special rates for parking and certain parking spaces.
"It is an initiative that I am pleased to see" observes Giuseppe Tornatore and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna by putting in place other measures.
It is clear, however, that, in order to contrast the super power of multiplexes, traditional rooms also need to improve the quality of sound and image, because today's audience is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important to me: the closing of the Supercinema of Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make "New cinema Paradiso" to which I had already thought for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass the Rialto, or the Quirinal of Via Nazionale, now closed, where I have experienced so much shared emotions, I turn from the other side to not see the panels darkened by the dust.
