When the energy is born from waves, now the bigs are starting.
This is a vast deposit that occupies more than 70% of the world's surface and now the world's largest energy companies are discovering it.
Vagues, currents, tides, these are the new renewable sources on which colosses like Chevron have laid their eyes, and now try to get their hands on them.
The possibility of obtaining energy from the movements of the sea has now been studied for hundreds of years, and in the 1970s, in conjunction with the first oil crisis, research intensified.
When the price of oil dropped around 1980, the idea of exploiting marine energy was put aside, but now the environmental authorities and the new increase in oil give the sector a big boost.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15% of the global electricity requirement could be covered by sea swell operating systems.
This amount would be twice as much as that produced by nuclear power plants.
And besides, there would be currents and tides..
Colosseum to attack.
The first company to rely on marine energy was the Enersis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build an installation in northern Portugal.
When the deal was announced, it would have been a real revolutionary step.
Two years after that, more and more of these companies, which have always been dedicated to traditional energy, rely on marine energy.
"Chevron is currently studying ocean energy technologies," said the spokesman for a company associated with the U.S. oil colossal, the Wall Street Journal, "and she assesses the possibilities of cooperating with us."
The cooperation in question involves obtaining a deliberate permit from the American Energy Commission, which is necessary to give rise to a project to exploit marine energy in Alaska.
